Distribution and habitat. Limestone outcrops and caves in the Maya Mountains and Sierra de los Cuchumatanes throughout most of Belize and portions of the Petén and Alta Verapaz departments in Guatemala , from 50–600 m altitude, more common at lower levels. “Found on limestone and dead wood, sometimes hanging by a thread. Some were in motion, but the larger part were attached to the rock or wood of similar color” (
Hinkley, 1920 : 44
). Commonly found among Mayan ruins. Locally abundant.

